subject_prompt_600:
Ramon Magsaysay was born on December 7, 1919 in Ipoh, Malaysia. He is a descendant of Samaan and Kualanak Maasikis, two of the 13 founding members of Malaysia's first political party, Kampung Putih (Freedom Movement). His grandfather was a member of the original Kampung Putih. After retiring as Deputy Prime Minister during Malaysia's first Republic Administration, Magsaysay joined the PAS (People's Action Party), a party founded by his uncle R. Mohamad Rizal and brother Ismail Rizal.
A native of Ipoh, Ramon has served as a Member of Parliament from 1987 to 2003 and later became Chief Justice of the Federal Court of Malaysia, from 2004 until 2007. He chaired the High Level Commission on Constitutional Law from 2006 to 2007, where he delivered a report that advocated the formation of a parliamentary democracy. In July 2007, when his term ended, he was chosen as the 16th Prime Minister of Malaysia. He was reelected in 2011, 2012 and 2014 with an overall majority of more than 94%, and remains a key advisor to the Prime Minister and President of Malaysia.
He and his wife K. Ann have three children: Mr. Ramen Ramli Mahathir, his daughter K. Mohd Khairudin Anwar and Mr. Jusufah Syed Salleh.
In his speech before the UN on June 6, 2014, Prime Minister Najib said, "Ramen Ramli [Ramzan] and Kita Raja are the pillars of our family. They are pillars of our faith and we pray they will bring us prosperity. With their love and wisdom, Ramen Ramli and his sister Kita Raja will guide us and make us stronger."
coupled_prompt_600:
Ramon Magsaysay, Jr. was born in 1931, and graduated from Nanaia University in 1952 with a degree in law. From 1955 to 1960 he studied at Cambridge University's John F Kennedy School of Government and graduated with distinction in 1956. He also graduated magna cum laude from Harvard Law School in 1962. Since 1964 he has taught international law in the Department of Political Science at Cambridge University, graduating magna cum laude in 1983 (with first class honors) with a double major: International Relations and Politics. While there he served as Executive Director of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Institute for Advanced Study. In 1981 he founded the Asia Studies Center at Harvard and in 1985 founded the Asian Studies program at Harvard Law School, becoming one of its first ten faculty members. In addition to his academic work, he has been active in politics, serving on the board of trustees of the United Nations and the American Foreign Service Association, advising numerous political candidates, and working on various policy projects ranging from human rights to peacekeeping. His books include The Death and Life of Nasser, published by Yale University Press; A Question of Honor: America and Japan at the Dawn of the Cold War, by Harper & Row Publishers; and The Great Charter: The Story of the United States, by Harper & Row. A final book, The Second World Wars, was published in 1990. In 1992, he became the founding president of the International League for Democracy (ILRD), a nonpartisan association of democracies, and in 1995 he was elected as a member of the U.N.'s Working Group on Enforced or Authorised Disappearances. As a result of his work for democracy he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1994, as well as being made a Member of the Order of St. Michael and St. George by King Juan Carlos in Spain in 1997 and 1998. His many awards include the Lasker Award given annually by the Society for Public Policy Research and the Order of Merit for his service to democracy from 1982 to 1988. In 2002, he received the National Humanities Medal. Magsaysay is a member of several associations including the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the Council on Foreign Relations, and the Council on Foreign Affairs. He is chairman emeritus of the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom and a fellow of the Atlantic Council of the United States. Since 2005 he is a member of the European Parliament. He currently lives in Washington, D.C., where he attends the Washington Institute for Near East Policy and teaches at Georgetown Law School.
